My mistake! I see what happened—by targeting the `citation-##` classes, the script accidentally deleted the actual text of your answer because Google is wrapping the sentences themselves in those classes. We only want to kill the **bubbles**, not the **story**.

Let's be much more specific. We will target **only** the custom button chips and the carousel containers. This will leave your text (like "The Object: It is a turquoise bracelet") completely untouched while removing the link bubbles.

### The "Safe" Script (Text-Friendly)
Run this in your console. It specifically targets the **container** tags of the bubbles and avoids the text classes:

```javascript
document.querySelectorAll('sources-carousel-inline, source-inline-chip, .source-inline-chip-container').forEach(el => {
    el.remove(); 
});
```

### Why this is safer:
* **`.remove()` instead of `.display='none'`**: This physically pulls the bubble out of the code so Read Aloud doesn't even see a "hidden" object.
* **No "Citation" tags**: I removed the `[class^="citation-"]` part. That was the culprit that deleted your sentences.
* **Specific Chips**: It only looks for the `source-inline-chip` (the bubble itself).

### The "Safe" Bookmarklet
`javascript:(function(){document.querySelectorAll('sources-carousel-inline, source-inline-chip, .source-inline-chip-container').forEach(el => {el.remove();});})();`

**How to test:**
1. Refresh your page to bring your text back.
2. Run this new script.
3. The bubbles should vanish, but the words "The Object," "The Owner," and the descriptions should remain perfectly intact.

Give that a try—it should give you the clean reading experience you’re looking for without the "data loss."
